5000|$|The Abgeltungsteuer (German, from Abgeltung [...] "payment", [...] "compensation" [...] + Steuer [...] "tax") is a {{flat tax}} on private <b>income</b> <b>from</b> <b>capital.</b> It is used in Germany, Austria, and Luxembourg.|$|E
50|$|The {{origins of}} the income tax on gains from capital assets did not {{distinguish}} capital gains from ordinary income. From 1913 to 1921, <b>income</b> <b>from</b> <b>capital</b> gains were taxed at ordinary rates, initially up to a maximum rate of 7 percent.|$|E
40|$|The bachelor’s thesis {{outlines}} the optimization of the Tax Liability. The {{goal of this}} paper is to scheme out the tax liability of the taxpayer with <b>income</b> <b>from</b> dependent activities, <b>income</b> <b>from</b> business activity and other independent gainful activity, <b>income</b> derived <b>from</b> <b>capital</b> and <b>income</b> <b>from</b> leasing using the income split among cooperative persons or joint taxation of marrieds...|$|R
