50|$|Taxes on <b>income</b> derived <b>from</b> <b>capital</b> (e.g., {{financial}} assets, {{property and}} businesses) primarily affect higher income groups, {{who own the}} vast majority of capital. For example, in 2010 approximately 81% of stocks were owned by the top 10% income group and 69% by the top 5%. Only about one-third of American households have stock holdings more than $7,000. Therefore, since higher-income taxpayers have a much higher share of their income represented by capital gains, lowering taxes on capital income and gains increases after-tax income inequality.|$|R
